  "prompt": "What are some cultural faux pas in Hungary?",
  "response": "Navigating cultural norms abroad can be a nuanced task, and Hungary is no exception. Here are some key cultural faux pas to keep in mind when in Hungary:\n\n1. **Addressing People:** Always use titles or formal greetings until invited to use first names. This is particularly important in professional or formal settings.\n\n2. **Handshakes:** Hungarians tend to offer firm handshakes, but it's important to wait for a woman to extend her hand first in mixed company.\n\n3. **Public Conduct:** Avoid loud or boisterous behavior in public spaces; Hungarians value polite, low-key demeanor.\n\n4. **Table Manners:** When dining, wait for the host to initiate the meal and use cutlery properly. It\u2019s also considered respectful to keep your hands visible and elbows off the table while eating.\n\n5. **Wine Toast:** Always make eye contact while clinking glasses and never do so with beer. Throughout history, toasting with beer has been associated with negative connotations due to historical events.\n\n6. **Gifting:** Offering gifts shows appreciation, but avoid overly extravagant presents. If invited to a Hungarian home, bringing flowers or a bottle of wine is well received. Just be cautious with choosing the flowers' number and type \u2014 avoid yellow flowers and giving an even number.\n\n7. **Punctuality:** Being on time is expected and valued in Hungary. If you\u2019re running late, inform your host as a courtesy.\n\n8. **Personal Space:** Respect personal space and avoid overly familiar physical contact unless you know the person well.\n\n9. **Sensitive Topics:** Steer clear of discussions around sensitive historical events or political issues unless you have established mutual understanding and trust.\n\n10. **Dress Code:** Dress modestly and conservatively in churches and traditional establishments.\n\nBy being mindful of these cultural norms, you can foster goodwill and create smoother interactions while visiting Hungary.",
